            <fr:title text="Ideal">Ideal</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">Dummit and Foote <fr:link href="/dummit-2004-abstract/" title="Abstract Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/dummit-2004-abstract/" display-uri="dummit-2004-abstract" type="local">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> Section 7.3</fr:meta>
            <fr:meta name="source">Artin <fr:link href="/artin-2010-algebra/" title="Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/artin-2010-algebra/" display-uri="artin-2010-algebra" type="local">Algebra</fr:link> Section 11.3</fr:meta>
            <fr:meta name="source">Hungerford <fr:link href="/hungerford-1974-algebra/" title="Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/hungerford-1974-algebra/" display-uri="hungerford-1974-algebra" type="local">Algebra</fr:link> Section III.2</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/ring-0001/" title="Ring" uri="http://localhost:8000/ring-0001/" display-uri="ring-0001" type="local">Ring</fr:link>. A <html:dfn>(Two-Sided) Ideal</html:dfn> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is a nonempty subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I\subseteq  R]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is a <fr:link href="/ra-000Z/" title="Left ideal of a ring" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-000Z/" display-uri="ra-000Z" type="local">left ideal</fr:link> and a <fr:link href="/ra-0010/" title="Right ideal of a ring" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-0010/" display-uri="ra-0010" type="local">right ideal</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>.</html:p><html:p>Furthermore, when <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I\neq  R]]></fr:tex> we say <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is a <html:dfn>Proper (two-sided) ideal</html:dfn> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>.</html:p><html:p>Some authors use the notation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I\mathrel {\trianglelefteq }R]]></fr:tex> to indicate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is an ideal of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>, as well as <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I\mathrel {\triangleleft }R]]></fr:tex> for proper ideals, analogous to the notation used for <fr:link href="/gr-002P/" title="Normal subgroup" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-002P/" display-uri="gr-002P" type="local">Normal subgroup</fr:link>s.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>(1) For commutative rings, any left ideal is also a right ideal, and so we just speak of "ideals".</html:p>
<html:p>(2) "Ideal" originally described "ideal elements" adjoined to a ring, which are not "real".</html:p>
<html:p>(3) A two-sided ideal forms a <fr:link href="/ra-000Q/" title="Subring" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-000Q/" display-uri="ra-000Q" type="local">Subring</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>, same for one-sided ideals of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
<html:p>(4) Traditionally, the historic notation used to indicate we're working with ideals was to use fraktur letters (<fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {a}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {b}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {c}]]></fr:tex>, and so on). This was a horrible decision. Modern conventions use <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex>, and variants using apostrophes or indices.</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
