            <fr:title text="Quotient Ring">Quotient Ring</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">Dummit and Foote <fr:link href="/dummit-2004-abstract/" title="Abstract Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/dummit-2004-abstract/" display-uri="dummit-2004-abstract" type="local">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> Proposition 7.3.6</fr:meta>
            <fr:meta name="source">Artin <fr:link href="/artin-2010-algebra/" title="Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/artin-2010-algebra/" display-uri="artin-2010-algebra" type="local">Algebra</fr:link> Section 11.3</fr:meta>
            <fr:meta name="source">Hungerford <fr:link href="/hungerford-1974-algebra/" title="Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/hungerford-1974-algebra/" display-uri="hungerford-1974-algebra" type="local">Algebra</fr:link> Theorem III.2.7</fr:meta>
            <fr:meta name="source">MML <fr:link href="https://mizar.uwb.edu.pl/version/current/html/ring_1.html#K2" type="external">ring_1:def 6</fr:link></fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/ring-0001/" title="Ring" uri="http://localhost:8000/ring-0001/" display-uri="ring-0001" type="local">Ring</fr:link> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[I\mathrel {\trianglelefteq } R]]></fr:tex> be an <fr:link href="/ra-0011/" title="Ideal" uri="http://localhost:8000/ra-0011/" display-uri="ra-0011" type="local">Ideal</fr:link> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>. Then the additive quotient group <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R/I]]></fr:tex> is a ring under the following binary operators
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[(r+I)+(s+I)=(r+s)+I]]></fr:tex>
and
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[(r+I)(s+I)=(rs)+I]]></fr:tex>
for all <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[r,s\in  R]]></fr:tex>.</html:p><html:p>Furthermore,
<html:ol><html:li>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is commutative, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R/I]]></fr:tex> is commutative.</html:li>
<html:li>If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex> is unital, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R/I]]></fr:tex> is unital.</html:li></html:ol></html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>17</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>To prove well-definedness, we should prove <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R/I]]></fr:tex> equipped with these operators form a ring (since existence and uniqueness follow from the quotient group). Specifically, that multiplication exists and satisfies the various axioms.</html:p><html:span class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
