            <fr:title text="Cosets of stabilizer are bijective with the orbits">Cosets of stabilizer are bijective with the orbits</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>theorem</fr:taxon>
            <fr:meta name="source">Artin's <fr:link href="/artin-2010-algebra/" title="Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/artin-2010-algebra/" display-uri="artin-2010-algebra" type="local">Algebra</fr:link> Proposition 6.8.4</fr:meta>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> be a <fr:link href="/gr-000G/" title="Group" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-000G/" display-uri="gr-000G" type="local">Group</fr:link>, let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> be a set, suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> <fr:link href="/gr-004Y/" title="Left group action" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-004Y/" display-uri="gr-004Y" type="local">acts</fr:link> on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>. Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x\in  X]]></fr:tex> be arbitrary. The function
<fr:tex display="block"><![CDATA[\begin {split}\overline {f}\colon  &G/G_{x}\to  G\cdot  x\\ &gG_{x}\mapsto  g\cdot  x\end {split}]]></fr:tex>
is a bijection between the <fr:link href="/gr-003H/" title="Left cosets of a subgroup" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-003H/" display-uri="gr-003H" type="local">left cosets</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G/G_{x}]]></fr:tex> and the orbit <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G\cdot  x]]></fr:tex>.</html:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>16</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>proof</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>We need to show <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {f}]]></fr:tex> is a well-defined <fr:link href="/nst-0014/" title="Function" uri="http://localhost:8000/nst-0014/" display-uri="nst-0014" type="local">Function</fr:link>. We see if <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[aG_{x}=bG_{x}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a^{-1}b\in G_{x}]]></fr:tex> and by definition of the <fr:link href="/gr-004C/" title="Stabilizer" uri="http://localhost:8000/gr-004C/" display-uri="gr-004C" type="local">Stabilizer</fr:link> we see <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a^{-1}b\cdot  x=x]]></fr:tex> and therefore <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a\cdot  x=b\cdot  x]]></fr:tex>. Therefore this is a well-defined function.</html:p>
<html:p>Reading this argument backwards, we establish <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {f}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/ela-001J/" title="Injective function" uri="http://localhost:8000/ela-001J/" display-uri="ela-001J" type="local">injective</fr:link>.</html:p>
<html:p>Since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {f}]]></fr:tex> maps <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[gG_{x}]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\cdot  x]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[g\cdot  x]]></fr:tex> can be an arbitrary element of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G\cdot  x]]></fr:tex>, this means <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {f}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/ela-001I/" title="Surjective function" uri="http://localhost:8000/ela-001I/" display-uri="ela-001I" type="local">surjective</fr:link>. Hence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {f}]]></fr:tex> is <fr:link href="/ela-001K/" title="Bijective function" uri="http://localhost:8000/ela-001K/" display-uri="ela-001K" type="local">bijective</fr:link>.</html:p><html:span class="qed">∎</html:span></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
