            <fr:title text="Preferatory notes">Preferatory notes</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><html:p>This is loosely following the material covered in the Math 5 series at <fr:link href="/caltech.edu" title="California Institute of Technology" uri="http://localhost:8000/caltech.edu" display-uri="caltech.edu" type="local">California Institute of Technology</fr:link> (based on Dummit and Foote's <fr:link href="/dummit-2004-abstract/" title="Abstract Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/dummit-2004-abstract/" display-uri="dummit-2004-abstract" type="local">Abstract Algebra</fr:link>) or the Math 150 series at <fr:link href="/ucdavis.edu" title="University of California, Davis" uri="http://localhost:8000/ucdavis.edu" display-uri="ucdavis.edu" type="local">University of California, Davis</fr:link> (based on Artin's <fr:link href="/artin-2010-algebra/" title="Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/artin-2010-algebra/" display-uri="artin-2010-algebra" type="local">Algebra</fr:link>).</html:p><html:p>We have already seen a number of different "species" of Mathematical Gadgets, like:</html:p><html:ul><html:li><fr:link href="/vectsp-0001/" title="Vector Space" uri="http://localhost:8000/vectsp-0001/" display-uri="vectsp-0001" type="local">Vector Space</fr:link></html:li>
<html:li><fr:link href="/field-0001/" title="Field" uri="http://localhost:8000/field-0001/" display-uri="field-0001" type="local">Field</fr:link></html:li>
<html:li><fr:link href="/ca-000K/" title="Metric Space" uri="http://localhost:8000/ca-000K/" display-uri="ca-000K" type="local">Metric Space</fr:link></html:li>
<html:li><fr:link href="/gt-0002/" title="Topological space" uri="http://localhost:8000/gt-0002/" display-uri="gt-0002" type="local">Topological space</fr:link></html:li>
<html:li><fr:link href="/nst-0001/" title="Set" uri="http://localhost:8000/nst-0001/" display-uri="nst-0001" type="local">Set</fr:link></html:li></html:ul><html:p>It turns out, all the information which was really interesting was encoded in the "structure-preserving transformations" between them. (That was the bulk of our time spent studying <fr:link href="/ela/" title="Elementary linear algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/ela/" display-uri="ela" type="local">Elementary linear algebra</fr:link> and <fr:link href="/ila/" title="Intermediate linear algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/ila/" display-uri="ila" type="local">Intermediate linear algebra</fr:link>, after all!)</html:p><html:p>We can form an abstraction describing this situation where we have a [gadget] and [transformations] between them: this is category theory.</html:p><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>http://localhost:8000/iaa-0005/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>iaa-0005</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/iaa-0005/</fr:route><fr:title text="Traditional way of teaching abstract algebra">Traditional way of teaching abstract algebra</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>The traditional way we teach undergraduates is by introducing several types of gadgets in abstract algebra in the following order:</html:p><html:ol><html:li>Initially, there's some discussion of set theory sufficient for developing algebra. This is "time honored tradition" starting with van der Waerden's book.</html:li>
<html:li>When the structure-preserving transformations leave something invariant (e.g., <fr:link href="/vectsp-001P/" title="Invariant subspace" uri="http://localhost:8000/vectsp-001P/" display-uri="vectsp-001P" type="local">Invariant subspace</fr:link>s in linear algebra), composing such transformations also leaves the thing invariant. This is the guiding intuition of what a "symmetry" is, and the "collection of symmetries" is precisely what a "group" is (originally, they were a "group of symmetries" or a <html:em>symmetry group</html:em>).</html:li>
<html:li><html:p>(a) But we also saw how, e.g., square matrices have a neat <fr:link href="/ela-000B/" title="Matrix Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/ela-000B/" display-uri="ela-000B" type="local">algebraic structure</fr:link> with matrix addition and matrix multiplication. They act like a "number system". This is precisely what is studied with number ring (or just a <fr:link href="/ring-0001/" title="Ring" uri="http://localhost:8000/ring-0001/" display-uri="ring-0001" type="local">Ring</fr:link>). A sufficiently nice ring is a <fr:link href="/field-0001/" title="Field" uri="http://localhost:8000/field-0001/" display-uri="field-0001" type="local">Field</fr:link>.</html:p>
<html:p>(b) We can generalize linear algebra to describe "vector spaces over arbitrary rings", and these are modules.</html:p></html:li>
<html:li>Galois theory is offered as the pinnacle of abstract algebra, connecting group theory to field theory. Honestly, I never understood the excitement behind Galois theory, since the beautiful parts of it are just the representation theory of groups (describing how "the same symmetries appearing in different situations").</html:li></html:ol><html:p>This is just the first 7 chapters of van der Waerden's <fr:link href="/van-der-waerden-1949-modern1/" title="Modern Algebra, Vol. I" uri="http://localhost:8000/van-der-waerden-1949-modern1/" display-uri="van-der-waerden-1949-modern1" type="local">Modern Algebra, Vol. I</fr:link>. Most textbooks have followed this manner of presentation: Dummit and Foote's <fr:link href="/dummit-2004-abstract/" title="Abstract Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/dummit-2004-abstract/" display-uri="dummit-2004-abstract" type="local">Abstract Algebra</fr:link> covers this material in the first 14 chapters; Hungerford's <fr:link href="/hungerford-1974-algebra/" title="Algebra" uri="http://localhost:8000/hungerford-1974-algebra/" display-uri="hungerford-1974-algebra" type="local">Algebra</fr:link> does this in the first 6 chapters.</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree show-metadata="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>15</fr:day></fr:date><fr:uri>http://localhost:8000/iaa-0006/</fr:uri><fr:display-uri>iaa-0006</fr:display-uri><fr:route>/iaa-0006/</fr:route><fr:title text="Modern ways to teach abstract algebra">Modern ways to teach abstract algebra</fr:title></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><html:p>The more modern approaches to teaching abstract algebra incorporates some degree of category theory into the mix.</html:p><html:p>Aluffi's <fr:link href="/aluffi-2009-algebra/" title="Algebra: Chapter 0" uri="http://localhost:8000/aluffi-2009-algebra/" display-uri="aluffi-2009-algebra" type="local">Algebra: Chapter 0</fr:link> is perhaps the most bold attempt to reorganize abstract algebra around category theory entirely. Instead of ending at Galois theory, Aluffi concludes with homological algebra.</html:p><html:p>Some ideas from the traditional approach (like "groups with operators") turn out to be confused and muddled (which should be replaced with groups acting on other groups).</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
   
   <fr:tree show-metadata="false" toc="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link href="/alex-nelson/" title="Alex Nelson" uri="http://localhost:8000/alex-nelson/" display-uri="alex-nelson" type="local">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:date><fr:year>2025</fr:year><fr:month>12</fr:month><fr:day>14</fr:day></fr:date><fr:taxon>remark</fr:taxon></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
<html:p>If I had to teach abstract algebra to undergraduates, I am torn between the traditional approaches (starting from van der Waerden's <html:em>Moderne Algebra</html:em> onwards) which I just outlined, and more modern adaptations which wrap everything in the framework of category theory. Aluffi's <html:em>Algebra: Chapter Zero</html:em> seemingly attempts a happy medium, and I am unhappy with it.</html:p>
<html:p>One fortunate aspect to Forester is that I'm not forced to choose one or the other. I can outline the "traditional" presentation of topics, and the "modern" presentation of topics, and allow the reader to pick which manner of presentation they wish to peruse.</html:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
</fr:mainmatter>
